John Edward: Foreign language skills are essential for global citizens
Private schools in Scotland still maintain their academic excellence, which was continued in 2018 with a rewarding series of academic results, reinforced both individually and collectively in terms of sport, art, music and community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, sponsored by the Scottish Council for Private Schools (SCIS), are working to deliver the best quality of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to equip students with deep and broad knowledge, as well as career orientation and status as global citizens.
As an educational subdiscipline that can design and run the school’s distinctive curriculum, we see modern foreign languages continuing to be a popular and chosen topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in the language he understands, what he says comes to his mind.
If you talk to him in his own language, the words will come to his mind.”
This is a compelling message that we don’t just rely on English for our desire to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the recent exams this year, we can see that foreign languages are leading in the rankings with the best grades in private school subjects.
A total of 68 percent of foreign language students scored higher than A.
Data collected from SCIS’ 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students scored more than an A in Chinese, along with 72 percent learned German, 69 percent learned French and 63 percent learned Spanish as well.
This suggests that private schools in Scotland are moving in the direction of treating foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will not be able to avoid in the future.
Elective foreign language subjects are being considered as STEM majors (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in private school programs as well as elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the British Council for Skills and Careers in 2014 found that among the reasons employers have difficulty finding people is due to a lack of foreign language skills.
As a result, foreign language skills are becoming more and more practical in order to equip young people for professional practice in the future.
With more and more career prospects in need of a foreign language, these skills become practical in an increasingly flat world.
No matter how people choose the job, if they learn a second language, they will get a real advantage in the future when they have such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly in the language of the natives themselves, a multilingual person will obviously lead every challenge.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom, 75 percent of them are unable to practice a simple passage in another foreign language, and only French is the only foreign language that accounts for a single number of units, 15 percent.
That’s why investing in foreign language teaching is so important for children today.
Having multilingual hands, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with brighter potential to find a real job.
In Scotland, each school teaches different languages.
Some schools will focus on more modern foreign languages, while others will teach foreign languages that are considered important to the UK in their vision for 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever interests children, there are a variety of foreign languages to choose from within private schools, along with a team of teachers with expertise in the profession.
Private schools in Scotland focus on providing an academic environment that prepares and equips children with skills essential to success, no matter what the future holds.
There is no denying that, in an international business environment, foreign languages will continue to be extremely important to the future of the nation, which should be replicated in education.
In fact, modern foreign languages should be considered “international communication skills.”
Private schools will continue to offer this opportunity to Scottish youth: diverse and outstanding.
There can be no other choice.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Private School Board.
