North Korea's foreign minister, speaking to the United Nations on Saturday, said the sanctions were being maintained and deepened its mistrust of the United States and, in this situation, there was no way for it to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho, speaking at the annual session of the United Nations General Assembly, said North Korea had taken "many goodwill measures" over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test bases and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see a similar move from the U.S. side," he said.
“If we can’t trust the American side, we won’t be confident in our national security, and under such a situation, there’s no way we can unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
Although Ri echoed North Korea’s familiar complaint that Washington rejects denuclearization “in stages” and that North Korea will receive the corresponding benefit of taking steps, his remarks this time have the notable point of not rejecting a unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has previously refused.
Ri mentioned a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an incumbent U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12. In this statement, Kim pledged to work towards "nuclear disarmament on the Korean Peninsula," while Trump promised security guarantees for North Korea.
North Korea is still trying to find a way to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States insists it must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington also opposes calls for easing harsh international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'de-nuclear disarmament first' and increases pressure with sanctions to achieve its goals in a coercive manner, even opposing the 'declaration of an end to the war'," Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is just a wild dream of people who don’t understand us.
But the problem here is that these sustained sanctions continue to lose our trust.”
Ri made no mention of plans to hold a second summit between Kim and Trump, as the U.S. leader presented at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the foreign minister referred to three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: “If the negotiating side on the nuclear disarmament issue is South Korea, not the United States, then the denuclearization talks on the Korean peninsula will not be in the current standoff.”
Ri’s tone, however, was different from last year’s, when he told the General Assembly that North Korea’s missile launch on the U.S. mainland was inevitable on a suicide mission after Trump called Kim a “missile man.”
Last year at the United Nations, Trump threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, but this year praised Kim for bravely taking steps to disarm, but Trump also stressed that much more needs to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea denuclearizes.
