Harvard students take a course on full rest
In an effort to combat machine-pressure learning culture, with 'night owl students' drinking coffee instead of water, a new course at Harvard University this year has encouraged all college students to sleep more.
Students at the world’s number one university often don’t know the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Women’s Hospital and Brigham designed the course, and he himself believes it is the first of its kind in the United States.
Inspiration started this course after he took a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on the learning process.
“After the end of the talk, a female student came up to me and said, ‘Why do you not know this until the last year?’
She said no one had told her about the importance of sleep, which really surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was introduced for the first time this year, explains to students how the importance of good sleep habits improves academic and athletic performance and improves their overall health.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s medical services, said the school decided to introduce the course after finding students with severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course covers a wide range of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a dorm room image in which students can click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise machines and books to learn about how caffeine, light, and sleep deprivation affect sports performance, as well as the importance of forming a punctual bedtime routine.
In another section, participants were asked to learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Then the university campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this course cannot immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know — just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke,” Czeisler added.
The culture of proud “night owl students” still exists, he said, while modern technologies and increasing pressure on students lead to sleep deprivation is an increasingly serious problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, good sleep quality should become a student’s ‘secret weapon’ to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety – even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep causes the brain to fall into a state of hunger, leading us to constantly be hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student in California who is studying biology, chemistry and physics, helped Czeisler design the course, and he took one of the classes last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to make an effort to organize a course throughout the school.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all graduate students to take a similar program of study before starting to compete in the main course.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students consider when setting bedtime alarms, waking hours, and being aware of the harmful effects of the ‘green light’ emitted by electronic displays and LEDs, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble sleeping.
