The National Trust has been eavesdropping on the secret lives of bats.
A new study is underway at a site in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use natural landscapes to hunt for food.
It is hoped that these findings will shed light on the behavior of this unique flying mammal and guide future conservation activities.
The study, led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, tracked the journeys of common bats, soprano pipistrelles, brown-eared bats and Daubenton bats at the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations around the research site to monitor the activity of these bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
The audio analyst will analyze all the recordings and determine the frequency of the bat’s sound and the purpose of playing the sound of each particular bat genera.
After that, maps and habitat reports of bats will be created to get a detailed picture of the natural landscape of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS’s nature conservation advisor, hopes the results will help determine which habitats are most important for bats and how each species inhabits that environment.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management activities of organisms, such as planting grasslands and the best way to conserve forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect bats’ bean rigs and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting systems, fly trap paper, some chemical treatments for building materials, as well as pet cat attacks can also pose risks to bats.
Bats are not completely blind.
However, due to the habit of hunting at night, the ears are more useful than the eyes when stalking and catching prey.
They use an extremely sophisticated echo positioning technique to identify obstacles on the flight path.
The NTS is responsible for taking care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, while attaching special importance to bats.
The organization has ten trained professionals who regularly conduct surveys, tests and sometimes participate in animal rescues.
The organization even established Scotland's first and only bat sanctuary at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway. It is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Managing the land, David Thompson said the land was their ideal territory.
“Threave is a great habitat for bats,” he said.
“We have a lot of old buildings, a lot of trees and a good living environment.
But there’s still a lot of mystery about bats, so work here and at other facilities will help us better understand what bats need to grow further.”
He stressed the importance of examining bat life before conservation in the estates, because inadvertently destroying their breeding trenches could kill up to 400 females and vomits, almost completely destroying the population.
Bats are protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb, or destroy their bean trusses.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an employee of the Scottish Bat Conservation Fund, encouraged the community to join in helping.
“We still need to learn more about bats, and with many species, we don’t know how far apart their populations are.”
