Red tides: Red tide density decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Association shows that red tide density has declined in much of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, algae blooms have been reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – which causes red tide densities to drop.
Red tides spread for about 130 miles along the northern coast of Pinellas to southern Lee County.
Small patches were also found within 10 miles of Hillsborough County, but fewer sites than last week.
Red tides have also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium density along the coast or off the coast of Pinellas County has been reported over the past week, low to high density off the coast of Hillsborough County, low to high density in Manatee County, low to high density off the coast of Sarasota County, low to high density in Charlotte County, low to high density along the coast or offshore in Lee County, and low density in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Respiratory irritability has not been reported in northwest Florida in the past week.
